'''Tharanga Goonetilleke''' is a [[soprano]] opera singer who was born in [[Badulla]], [[Sri Lanka]], but grew up in [[Ratmalana]]. Her singing ability was noticed by a music professor from [[Converse College]] while he was visiting Sri Lanka. She is the first woman from Sri Lanka to attend the [[Juilliard School]], one of the world's leading music schools. She currently lives in New York City, and her career in opera has received international attention.

==Education==
Goonetilleke began learning to sing in Sri Lanka at the age of 12 under the training of Christine Perera.<ref name=TSTSri>{{cite news|title=Tharanga returns to sing with SOSL|url=http://www.sundaytimes.lk/110206/Magazine/sundaytimesmagazine_03.html|accessdate=3 May 2014|newspaper=[[The Sunday Times (Sri Lanka)|The Sunday Times]]|date=6 February 2011}}</ref><ref name=SO>{{cite news|last=Perera|first=Mahes|title=From my heart|url=http://www.sundayobserver.lk/2005/08/07/fea34.html|accessdate=3 May 2014|newspaper=[[Sunday Observer (Sri Lanka)|Sunday Observer]]|date=7 August 2005}}</ref> She began attending Converse College in [[South Carolina]] in 2001 and graduated in 2005 with Bachelor of Music degree in Vocal Performance and a minor in biology.<ref name=TI>{{cite news|last=Wanasundera|first=Nanda P.|title=Tharanga Goonetilleke – Distinguished Lyric Soprano|url=http://www.island.lk/index.php?page_cat=article-details&page=article-details&code_title=17625|accessdate=3 May 2014|newspaper=[[The Island (Sri Lanka)|The Island]]|date=5 February 2011}}</ref><ref name=CC>{{cite news|last=Spigner|first=Sarah G.|title=Friends of the Petrie School of Music/Carlos Moseley Chamber Music Series Presents Tharanga Goonetilleke, Soprano, and Nathan Brandwein, Piano|url=http://www.converse.edu/event/2011-04-4/friends-petrie-school-musiccarlos-moseley-chamber-music-series-presents-tharanga-goo|accessdate=3 May 2014|newspaper=Converse College|date=4 April 2011}}</ref>

Representing South Carolina, she entered the [[Metropolitan Opera National Council Auditions]] and won.<ref name=TI/> Impressed by Goonetilleke's performance, the judges, who happened to be from the [[Juilliard School]], asked her whether she had considered attending graduate school.<ref name=TI/> Consequently, she decided to apply for admission to Juilliard,<ref name=TI/> and in 2005, she was the first Sri Lankan woman to be admitted to the Juilliard School and was provided a full tuition scholarship.<ref name=TSTSri/><ref name=SO/><ref name=NPR>{{cite news|title=Sri Lankan Opera Singer Followed Her Dream To American Stage|url=https://www.npr.org/2014/05/03/309213640/sri-lankan-opera-singer-followed-her-dream-to-american-stage|accessdate=3 May 2014|newspaper=[[NPR]]|date=3 May 2014}}</ref> Her living expenses were covered by President's Fund of Sri Lanka.<ref name=TI/> She graduated from Juilliard with a Master of Music in Voice and Opera.<ref name=TSTSri/>

==Career==
In 1998, Goonetilleke made her singing debut with the [[Symphony Orchestra of Sri Lanka]] (SOSL), after winning the SOSL concerto vocal competition in 1998.<ref name=TSTSri/><ref name=SO/> In 2010, she became a member of [[New York City Opera]],<ref name=TI/><ref>{{cite web|title=New York City Opera Announces Full Casting Details for the 2010–2011 Season|url=http://pressroom.nycopera.com/pr/nycopera/news/new-york-city-opera-announces-168320.aspx|publisher=New York City Opera|accessdate=4 May 2014|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130612061537/http://pressroom.nycopera.com/pr/nycopera/news/new-york-city-opera-announces-168320.aspx|archivedate=12 June 2013|df=dmy-all}}</ref> and has since performed in numerous operas such as ''[[Il trittico]]'',<ref name=Midgette>{{cite news|last=Midgette|first=Anee|title=Young cast of Puccini's "Il Trittico" makes Castleton Festival worth the trip|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2010/07/04/AR2010070404155.html|accessdate=3 May 2014|newspaper=Washington Post|date=5 July 2010}}</ref> ''[[Dialogues of the Carmelites]]'',<ref name=Moritz>{{cite news|last=Moritz|first=Alison|title=Towards the light: Juilliard students present Poulenc’s Dialogues|url=http://www.operatoday.com/content/2010/04/towards_the_lig.php|accessdate=3 May 2014|newspaper=Opera Today|date=27 April 2010}}</ref> ''[[La bohème]]'', ''[[Die Zauberflöte]]'', ''[[Iphigénie en Aulide]]'', and ''[[Ariodante]]''.<ref name=Ghosh>{{cite news|last=Ghosh|first=Palash|title=Tharanga Goonetilleke: A Sri Lankan Soprano Shatters Stereotypes About South Asians|url=http://www.ibtimes.com/tharanga-goonetilleke-sri-lankan-soprano-shatters-stereotypes-about-south-asians-1546059|accessdate=3 May 2014|newspaper=[[International Business Times]]|date=23 January 2014}}</ref> She has also performed in concerts in the United States,<ref name=NYT>{{cite news|last=Kozinn|first=Allan|title=Composers Who Made the Center Hold|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/01/29/arts/music/29focus.html|accessdate=3 May 2014|newspaper=New York Times|date=28 January 2010}}</ref><ref name=TH>{{cite news|last=Staff Reporter|title=A musical treat from Sri Lanka|url=http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-national/tp-newdelhi/a-musical-treat-from-sri-lanka/article2367691.ece|accessdate=3 May 2014|newspaper=[[The Hindu]]|date=18 August 2011}}</ref> Europe, India,<ref name=Ians>{{cite news|last=Ians|title=Lankan performers in India with classical repertoire|url=http://www.thaindian.com/newsportal/uncategorized/lankan-performers-in-india-with-classical-repertoire_100558031.html|accessdate=3 May 2014|newspaper=Thaindian News|date=20 August 2011}}</ref> and South Korea.<ref name=Ghosh/> Her 2011 concert tour in India was considered "timely" by the Sri Lankan High Commission in India since it helped foster a cultural dialogue between the two countries.<ref name=TH/>

==Personal life==
Goonetilleke grew up in Ratmalana, Sri Lanka, near the capital [[Colombo]].<ref name=Ghosh/> She first became interested in opera when she was thirteen when she heard soprano [[Kiri Te Kanawa]] sing.<ref name=Ghosh/> However, she did not think at that time that opera was a career option.<ref name=Ghosh/> A music professor from Converse College, Douglas Weeks,<ref name=SO/> was visiting Sri Lanka and heard her sing; he subsequently arranged for her admission to the college.<ref name=NPR/> She had planned to study medical science in Sri Lanka, but to her surprise, when her father found out about the offer for her to attend Converse College, he thought it was a good idea.<ref name=NPR/>

Her younger sister Eranga also attended Converse College and afterward obtained her master's degree in Opera and Musical Theater from [[Southern Illinois University]];<ref name=TI/> she is currently a faculty member at Converse College's Lawson Academy of the Arts.<ref>{{cite web|title=Lawson Academy Faculty|url=http://www.converse.edu/academics/school-arts/lawson-academy-arts/faculty-bios-0?page=1|publisher=Converse College|accessdate=4 May 2014}}</ref> Goonetilleke is married, has a daughter, and lives in New York City.<ref name=NPR/>

